Data Selection¶

For this project I have decided to make use of an official UK Government COVID-19 Dataset procured from Kaggle. The data itself has come from https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/ and has been scraped into multiple essential sheets using appropriate mining techniques provided from the corresponding developers guide. From this set, the data I am especially interested in includes overall numbers and breakdowns of regional cases from all across the UK as a whole. Specifically new and cumulative data on cases and deaths within 28 days of the publish date.

Before I can begin processing my data it is important to assess and see whether it is analytic ready:

  • The source of my data seems to be reliable as it initially was retrieved from government official sources concerning coronavirus cases.
  • As this set has been updated in the past month, the accuracy should be no issue, however I will be performing further checks in processing to ensure accuracy further
  • My chosen dataset if publicly available and as such can be accessed and assessed by users of any level
  • Data security and data privacy is not relevant to assessing this set as it is strictly to do with figures instead of personal records
  • The data seen in this set has information on regions individually, with opportunities to compare findings comparatively between them
  • As this is government processed data, we can assume that there is high consistency to it as it it gathered from an individual source
  • Finally, this data is relevant to our current time and situation making it a suitable source to mine

Hence it would seem that my data is ready and valid to be analyzed for this project

I have decided to make use of python to prepare, assess and visualise data to find and compare patterns, as it is widely used by data scientists worldwide due to the wide range of libraries and online resources. Data visualization in python is one of its highly utilised features when it comes to data science. The various libraries come with many features that enable Data Scientists to make elegant, highly customisable, and interactive plots. In the healthcare sector it is mainly used to create machine learning algorithms that are used in diagnostics, operations and predictive prognosis.

Data cleaning¶

Handle missing values in the data¶

To address the lack of data fount in the South East area I will be removing it all together as to not cause any conflicts with the other records when visualised, the other odd missing values will also be addressed later during the reducing section of this report. Below I am demonstrating how to locate I achieved the deleting process of an entire process:

  • Firstly isolating the south east data from the dataframe
  • Looking at the first head entry to locate the earliest date it was recorded
  • Thereafter filtering the Dataframe to exclude it from further usage
In [ ]:
# South East first entry date
southEast = df['areaName']=='South East'
df[southEast]['date'].head(1)

Data reduction¶

To reduce the number of records found in my dataset I first need to determine what it is I would like to present in my data visualisation. After all the work i have already done to filter and display this data, I will be

  • Producing graphics based on 2021 data strictly
    • Eliminating the other initial null values in both my cases and death fields
    • Providing a year overview of how the virus has affected us
  • Making educated and informed predictions based on
    • New cases and deaths by publish date
    • Cumulative cases and deaths by publish date
    • The death rate of patients
  • Allowing also for me to determine effects of seasons on the virus

With all of this determined I can clearly continue with the reduction of data, starting with dropping 3 columns from my existing dataframe. Thereafter filtering it according to the start date of 2021.

Cross industry standard process for data mining (CRIPS-DM)¶

In my project sofar I have decided to use a CRIPS-DM approach to analyse and mine my data:

  • It started with having a understanding of my project requirements
    • Finding and importing a medical dataset
    • To demonstrate data analytics
    • And data visualisation
    • That could be used in the healthcare sector
  • Data Understanding
    • The next important part is grasping and understanding my data
    • Which was needed to do the analysis above
    • My data consisted of mostly numerical data
      • With the dates being in datetime format
      • and all case and death data being floats
    • And some Nominal/Categorical data
      • AreaName specifically defines the areas in which cases and deaths are recorded
  • Data Preparation
    • Above my data has been mostly prepared based on set requirements
    • I have prepared and chosen to produce data for 2021
    • Solving null Values appropriately
    • Removing unnecessary col
    • All with the intention of splitting my data into
      • Training data builds the model
      • Testing data to measures success
  • Modeling
    • Once the data is prepared I will be using the information I have from visualisation
    • and create predictive models for it accordingly
  • Evaluation
    • Once it has all been produced the last step would be evaluating results accordingly
    • Creating and critiquing my work accordingly

plotDates = df.loc[:, 'date'].values

filterEOE = df['areaName']=='East of England'

filterL = df['areaName']=='London'

filterYH = df['areaName']=='Yorkshire and The Humber'

The above plot shows all of the regions on a singular graph, showing relatively equal growth all around the UK no matter the season, with the exception of London. This might be due to London being a travel hotspot as Heathrow is located there, possibly resulting in a higher rate of spreading the virus as people return from their journeys from various nations. Moreover while cases do seem to have decreased since the start of the year you can slowly see an increase around the 6th month all over the UK, which most likely corresponds to the the UK lockdown restrictions lifting on the 19th of July, as stated in by the the uk government and documented on the BBC (2021). Another worthwhile thing to note is that cases, as stated by the latest data have started to rise again, possibly indicating a yearly trend and being something that could be evaluated during prediction states.

I then proceeded to plot the regions separately on various subplots to have a better view on how each individual region is affected by the virus.

With some areas experiencing sudden growth in recent days possibly due to the new omnicron variant. As it is highly infectious, according to the CDC (2021), it would seem natural for it to start spiking in London as it is a travel hub like previously discussed.

As cases are only one aspect of the virus, I thought it would be worthwhile treating the deaths in the same way, plotting them as above and noting trends and patterns accordingly. This would provide a better understanding of the severity of the virus itself.

Prediction Model¶

  • Finally, construct a model that can make some predictions or forecast trends.

For my prediction models I both used a time series forecast and linear regression model respectively.

  • The time series will be estimating the amount of covid cases for a specific region
  • The linear regression model will attempt to predict
    • Deaths in the region
    • Cases in the region
In [ ]:
from pickle import TRUE
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
from statsmodels.tsa.ar_model import AutoRegResults
import numpy
from matplotlib import pyplot
from statsmodels.tsa.ar_model import AutoReg
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
import numpy
from math import sqrt

# create a difference transform of the dataset
def difference(dataset):
	diff = list()
	for i in range(1, len(dataset)):
		value = dataset[i] - dataset[i - 1]
		diff.append(value)
	return numpy.array(diff)

# Make a prediction give regression coefficients and lag obs
def predict(coef, history):
	yhat = coef[0]
	for i in range(1, len(coef)):
		yhat += coef[i] * history[-i]
	return yhat

filename = 'data.xlsx'
df = pd.read_excel(filename)

# Change here to region for differant results
areaName = 'London'

filter = df['areaName']== areaName
df = df[filter]
df = df[['date', 'newCasesByPublishDate']]

# fit an AR model and save the whole model to file
from pandas import read_csv
from statsmodels.tsa.ar_model import AutoReg
import numpy

# create a difference transform of the dataset
def difference(dataset):
	diff = list()
	for i in range(1, len(dataset)):
		value = dataset[i] - dataset[i - 1]
		diff.append(value)
	return numpy.array(diff)

# split dataset
X = df['newCasesByPublishDate'].values
Y = df['date'].values

size = int(len(X) * 0.28)
train, test = X[0:size], X[size:]
# train autoregression
model = AutoReg(train, lags=20, old_names=TRUE)
model_fit = model.fit()
coef = model_fit.params
# walk forward over time steps in test
history = [train[i] for i in range(len(train))]
predictions = list()
testing = list()
for t in range(len(test)):
	yhat = predict(coef, history)
	obs = test[t]
	predictions.append(yhat)
	testing.append(test[t])
	history.append(obs)
rmse = sqrt(mean_squared_error(test, predictions))
print('Test RMSE: %.3f' % rmse)

# plot
fill = len(X)-len(test)
fillArr = []
for x in range(fill):
  fillArr.append(None)
predictions = fillArr + predictions
testing = fillArr + testing

f = plt.figure()
f.set_figwidth(20)
f.set_figheight(10)

plt.plot(X)
plt.plot(testing)
plt.plot(predictions, color='red')
plt.ylabel('Cases',fontsize=13)
plt.xlabel('Duration (Days)',fontsize=13)
plt.title('Time Series Prediction of new Covid Cases in '+areaName, fontsize=15)
plt.grid(axis='x')
plt.show()

Test RMSE: 1359.369

This time series forecasts uses an autoregression model with a lag of 20 on our pre processed dataset to predict the forecast of new covid cases in the selected region. This data is transformed by differencing and then trained on 28% of the historical data, allowing regression coefficients that have been learned to be extracted and used for predictions. With every time step a prediction is made through coefficients with the actual observation made available and stored to be used as a lag value.

The firsts value printed is the Root Mean Squared Error of the predictions, meaning that there is about 1360 cases on average given the calculated data, giving an indications on how well this model is expected to perform. A graph is also created showing the actual observations (green) compared to the predictions (red).

Hereafter I have created 2 linear regression models to predict the current trend in deaths and also new cases of covid 19 within the region.

#Linear Regression
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

def ger_regression_predictions(features, intercept, slope):
    predicted_values = features*slope + intercept
    return predicted_values

filename = 'data.xlsx'
df = pd.read_excel(filename)

areaName = 'South West'
filter = df['areaName']==areaName
df = df[filter]
df = df[['newDeaths28DaysByPublishDate', 'date']]
data = df[['newDeaths28DaysByPublishDate', 'date']]

data['month'] = df['date'].dt.month
data['day'] = df['date'].dt.day
data['date'] = (df['date'].dt.month-1) * 31 + df['date'].dt.day

size = int(len(X) * 0.8)
train= data[:(int(len(X) * 0.8))]
test = data[(int(len(X) * 0.2)):]
# train autoregression
model = LinearRegression()
trainX = np.array(train[['date']])
trainY = np.array(train[['newDeaths28DaysByPublishDate']])
model.fit(trainX, trainY)
coef = model.coef_
intercept = model.intercept_

print(coef, intercept)

f = plt.figure()
f.set_figwidth(20)
f.set_figheight(10)

plt.plot(train['date'],train['newDeaths28DaysByPublishDate'])

plt.plot(trainX, coef*trainX + intercept, '-r')

estimated_values = ger_regression_predictions(180, intercept[0], coef[0][0])
print('estimated values: ',estimated_values)

plt.title('Linear regression of confirmed deaths by publish date in '+ areaName)
plt.ylim(bottom=-15, top=150)
plt.xlabel('Days')
plt.ylabel('New Deaths By Publish Date')
plt.grid(axis='x')
plt.show()

As opposed to the above death model, we can see that the cases of covid 19 are starting to rise again within the UK regions as there is a positive correlation with the 2 values, with an estimated 1652 average cases being predicted. This is most likely due to the previously mentioned omnicron virus being rapidly spread across the UK. Another possibility is that the vaccine is effective to the point where there are much less fatalities, but cases are still on the rise due to the new variant.

Evaluation¶

My results show both an increase in daily cases and a decrease of deaths overall within the UK, the former of which seems to be accurate when compared to data gathered from OurWorldInData as of 03/01/22. This is due to the newest omnicron variant running rampant int the UK at this moment and being highly infectious even with most citizens being vaccinated.

However, my linear regression model for deaths does not seem accurate due to the data being recorded 28 days prior to the date, indicating a steady decrease. However, when compared to the predictive models of HealthData we can see that there is predicted to be an increase in cases throughout the month. I would not say that my model was unsuccessful though, as the new variant was spontaneous and acted as an outlier event.

As such I would say that my analysis was relatively successful in what i could find and surmise from the given dataset, with the largest take away being that Covid-19 is quite unpredictable in nature as most any virus. While vaccines might prove effective, unless everyone in a community comes together to take it the virus can mutate and produce unforeseen consequences.
